 creating meaning that does not necessarily exist in the soundtrack or the script. Reading Sounds looks at closed-captioning as a potent source of meaning in rhetorical analysis. Through nine engrossing chapters, Sean Zdenek demonstrates how the choices captioners make affect the way deaf and hard of hearing viewers experience media. He draws on hundreds of real-life examples, as well as interviews with both professional captioners and regular viewers of closed captioning. Zdenek’s analysis is an engrossing look at how we make the audible visible, one that proves that better standards for closed captioning create a better entertainment experience for all viewers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aClosed captioning. 0aVisual communication. 70(DE-601)1840929490(DE-588)4373404-2aUntertitelgFilm2gnd 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / General.2bisacsh  apopular culture, cultural studies, technical commutation, rhetoric, composition, communication, media, closed captioned, sounds, movies, films, pictures, captioning, captioners, background noises, accents, speaking, sound, laughter, musical cues, music, silences, soundtrack, rhetorical analysis, entertainment, visual, subjectivity, logocentrism, talking.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022631264440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226312811423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226312811/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles